  "signature": "ed25519:b4e2d1c3f0a9e8d7c6b5a4f3e2d1c0b9a8f7e6d5c4b3a2f1e0d9c8b7a6f5e4d3",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA software (Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2) operates under a documented quality management system conforming to ISO 9001; version control, regression test suite, and change-control records are on file. Gradation 2 requires documented QMS and traceable version control.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under a vendor-maintained ISO 9001 QMS. Internal regression test suite covers all element types used in this model. Version and license records retained in the DePuy Synthes simulation archive. Gradation 2 is appropriate given the commercial, Class II device context and medium model risk."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10.1 and Ansys verification manual covering beam bending, contact, and large-displacement static analysis must be reproduced within 1% of analytical solutions. Gradation 2 requires successful completion of relevant published benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "Verification benchmarks for beam bending under combined axial and lateral loads, Hertzian contact, and geometric nonlinearity were executed and archived. All benchmark results agree with analytical or reference solutions to within 0.4%. Gradation 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A systematic mesh convergence study must demonstrate that the QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) change by less than 2% between the production mesh and a uniformly refined mesh with at least 1.5× linear element density. Gradation 3 requires a documented convergence study with quantified discretization error.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh densities (coarse, medium, fine) were evaluated. QoI differences between medium and fine meshes were 0.8%, 1.1%, and 0.6% for stiffness, yield force, and F40 respectively. Richardson extrapolation was applied; discretization error bounded at <1.5% for all QoIs. Production mesh corresponds to the medium density."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge to below 1×10⁻⁶ for force and displacement norms at every load step. Gradation 2 requires documented solver convergence with residual tolerances reported.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterations converged to residual norms below 1×10⁻⁷ for all 47 load steps across the ensemble of 11 model instances. No non-converged increments were accepted. Solver log files archived with simulation records."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Model setup was performed by a credentialed simulation engineer with 8 years of implant FEA experience. A second independent engineer reviewed boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions against the simulation plan prior to execution. Peer review checklist is on file. The required gradation level of 2 reflects the medium model risk and medium decision consequence; independent peer review of model inputs and boundary conditions satisfies this gradation. No structured acceptance criteria document was linked at the time of assessment because the peer-review procedure was treated as self-evidently sufficient given the team's established internal SOP."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V, linear elastic for UHMWPE block) must be justified by published material characterization data, and contact formulation (augmented Lagrange, frictional μ=0.2) must be validated against published tribological data for metal-on-polymer interfaces. Gradation 3 requires physics-based justification of all major model-form choices.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening parameters derived from ASTM E8 tensile coupon data (n=5 batches). UHMWPE elastic modulus sourced from ISO 5834-2 characterization. Frictional coefficient μ=0.2 supported by Dumbleton & Dumbleton (1978) and confirmed by sensitivity analysis (±0.05 μ changes QoI by <1.5%). Model form choices documented in the simulation technical report."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material properties must be sourced from lot-specific coupon testing or peer-reviewed literature with stated uncertainty bounds. Geometric inputs must be derived from CMM measurements of the actual test specimens. Gradation 3 requires traceability of all primary inputs to measurement data with quantified uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties sourced from lot-specific ASTM E8 tensile tests; UHMWPE block modulus from ISO 5834-2 characterization. Screw geometry from CMM measurement of three representative specimens (tolerance ±0.01 mm). Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (n=500 samples); 95th-percentile QoI uncertainty <3.2%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test specimens must be drawn from production lots with documented traceability; specimen geometry must be confirmed by CMM prior to testing. Gradation 3 requires a sample size sufficient to characterize variability and full geometric traceability.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories. All specimens drawn from production lots with full traceability to manufacturing records. CMM measurements confirmed dimensional conformance. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.8%, within expected manufacturing variability."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Testing must be performed under at least two distinct loading configurations or displacement rates to characterize sensitivity of QoIs to test condition variability. Gradation 3 requires multi-condition testing; Gradation 2 is accepted when a single standardized protocol (ASTM F1717) is used with full environmental documentation.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single displacement rate of 5 mm/min under ambient laboratory conditions (23±2°C, 50±10% RH). Only one loading configuration was evaluated. This limits the achieved level to Gradation 2; the gap relative to the required Gradation 3 is acknowledged and accepted given that ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard for this device class and no alternative configurations are prescribed by FDA guidance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions, loading) must be demonstrably equivalent to the experimental test conditions, with any discrepancies quantified and their effect on QoIs bounded by sensitivity analysis. Gradation 3 requires full input-by-input equivalency mapping with documented discrepancy analysis.",
      "rationale": "A formal input equivalency table maps each model parameter to its experimental counterpart. Boundary condition equivalency confirmed by comparing machine compliance (measured at 0.12 mm/kN) against model predictions. Fixture geometry modeled from engineering drawings verified against physical fixturing. All discrepancies bounded by sensitivity analysis; maximum QoI impact 1.8%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The E/uval metric must be below 1.96 for all primary QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement), and the percentage difference between mean predicted and mean experimental values must not exceed 10%. Gradation 3 requires a statistically rigorous comparison metric that accounts for both model and experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 0.84, yield force 1.12, F40 0.97 — all below 1.96. Percentage differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 5.7%, F40 2.9% — all below 10%. Comparison methodology follows FDA-recognized V&V 40 framework. Combined simulation and experimental uncertainty (uval) computed per ASME V&V 10 guidance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The selected QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) must be directly linked to the clinical and regulatory decision, with a documented argument that each QoI is mechanistically relevant to the failure mode of concern (fatigue and overload fracture of the screw). Gradation 3 requires explicit mechanistic linkage between QoIs and clinical risk.",
      "rationale": "Stiffness governs load sharing with the spinal column; yield force identifies onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to catastrophic failure. Clinical linkage documented in the Design V&V Plan. All three QoIs are explicitly referenced in FDA guidance for spinal fixation systems."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench testing) must be demonstrated to be representative of the intended COU (FEA supporting regulatory submission for a Class II spinal implant), with a documented argument addressing geometry, loading, material, and boundary condition representativeness. Gradation 3 requires a formal relevance argument covering all major dimensions of representativeness.",
      "rationale": "ASTM F1717 is the FDA-recognized consensus standard for pedicle screw construct mechanical testing. The validation geometry (7.5 mm non-cannulated screw in UHMWPE block at standard offset) matches the production device geometry. Loading (compression-bending) is the dominant in vivo mode for lumbar pedicle screws. Relevance argument documented in the Credibility Assessment Report, Section 4.3."
    }
  ],
